{"title_page": "Alexandra Bastedo", "text_new": "{{short description|British actress}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Alexandra Bastedo\n| image       = File:Alexandra Bastedo The Champions 1968.jpg\n| caption     = Bastedo in 1968\n| birthname   = Alexandra Lendon Bastedo\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date |df=yes|1946|03|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Hove]], Sussex, England\n| death_date  = {{death date and age |df=yes|2014|01|12|1946|03|09}}\n| death_place = Worthing, England\n| occupation  = Actress and writer\n| yearsactive = 1962\u20132014\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Patrick Garland]]|1980|2013|end=died}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexandra Lendon Bastedo''' (9 March 1946 \u2013 12 January 2014) was a British actress, best known for her role as secret agent Sharron Macready in the 1968 British espionage/science fiction adventure series ''[[The Champions]]''. She has been cited as a [[sex symbol]] of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/195819/What-happened-to-the-70s-sexpots |title=WHAT HAPPENED TO THE 70S SEXPOTS? |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=27 August 2010 |accessdate=3 November 2010}}</ref> Bastedo was a [[vegetarian]] and [[animal welfare]] advocate, and wrote a number of books on both subjects.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alexandra Bastedo |url=http://www.abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723021240/http://abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |archivedate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBastedo was born in [[Hove]], England. Her mother was of French, German and Italian descent while her Canadian-born father was of Spanish, Dutch, Scottish and native American extraction.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-alexandra-bastedo-actress-1-3266841|title=Obituary: Alexandra Bastedo, actress|last=Steven|first=Alasdair|date=14 January 2014|website=The Scotsman|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> She attended [[Brighton and Hove High School]] and Brighton School of Drama.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:The Champions.JPG|right|thumb|250px|Alexandra Bastedo with her co-stars [[William Gaunt]] and [[Stuart Damon]] in ''[[The Champions]]''.]]\nShe made her film debut as one of the title characters in [[William Castle]]'s poorly received ''[[13 Frightened Girls]]'' (1963). Bastedo received notice on the European continent, earning her the nickname, \"La Bastedo\". Although most familiar to viewers of 1960s TV, she was also known for her multilingual skills, speaking Italian, Spanish, French and German. This skill brought her to the attention of [[10 Downing Street]] to assist with translations and landed her the role of co-presenter of [[Miss World]] competitions with [[Peter Marshall (UK broadcaster)|Peter Marshall]] in the 1980s.\n\nIn 1979, she played in the series ''[[The Aphrodite Inheritance]]''. In 1988, Bastedo was the cover star for '[[Rank (album)|Rank]]', a live album by British band [[The Smiths]] that charted at number 2 on the British Album charts. In 1991, she appeared in a notable production of the psychological thriller ''[[Dangerous Obsession]]'' by [[N.J. Crisp]], opposite [[Marc Sinden]] and [[John Challis]], at the [[Mill at Sonning]]. In 1992, she appeared in \"Fat\" \u2013 the second broadcast episode of ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'', playing a 1960s model associate of Edina and Patsy. She was seen in two episodes of ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'' series, alongside [[Roger Moore]].\n\nIn 2006, Bastedo was reunited for the first time with her co-stars from ''[[The Champions]]'' to provide commentaries and an interview for a DVD release of the show. Still working as an actress, she appeared in ''[[Batman Begins]]'', and touring theatres in 2006 with a production of ''Beyond Reasonable Doubt'' alongside [[Leslie Grantham]] and [[Simon Ward]]. In 2008, she joined the cast of ''[[EastEnders]]'', playing Cynthia.<ref>[http://www.people.co.uk/news/tm_headline=60s-sexbomb-in-square%26method=full%26objectid=20607232%26siteid=93463-name_page News report on Bastedo]</ref><ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/latest/2008/08/28/exclusive-60s-star-alexandra-bastedo-is-new-eastender-115875-20714748/ Article in ''The Mirror Online'' about Bastedo]</ref> In January 2008, she appeared as co-presenter (with [[Ed Stewart]]) of \"The Magic of Mantovani\" at Lighthouse, Poole. The success of this concert led, the following year, to a second concert at the same venue, with the [[Mantovani|Mantovani Orchestra]], which she again co-presented.\n\n==Personal life==\nAlexandra was the one most beautiful british actresses of all times and she dated [[David Frost]] and [[Omar Sharif]] but turned down the advances of [[Steve McQueen]] who, she recalled, propositioned her with the line \"My wife doesn\u2019t understand me\". In the case of Sharif, the liaison lasted only a few weeks because of the actor's bridge-playing habit, his odd hours and that he took telephone numbers from other women.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alexandra Bastedo \u2013 obituary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10569081/Alexandra-Bastedo-obituary.html|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=3 Jan 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Mike Tomkies]], the Fleet Street journalist who abandoned the life of a celebrity reporter to live alone in the wilderness, lived with her for a while in Canada, and they talked of marriage, but she was prohibited from marrying by a contract for ''The Champions'' (1968 to 69). He said that she was the most stunningly beautiful creature he had ever seen.<ref>Telegraph obituary 15.11.16</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Alexandra married [[Patrick Garland]],<ref name=\"BBC13\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-22232389 \"Patrick Garland, theatre producer and director, dies aged 78\"], BBC News, 20 April 2013</ref> a director, writer and actor, at [[Chichester Cathedral]]; he became a long-serving director of the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]].<ref>''Who's Who'' (annually), entry for Patrick Garland</ref> Bastedo wrote a memoir, ''Beware Dobermanns, Donkeys and Ducks'', as well as several books on caring for cats and dogs. Her husband died on 19 April 2013.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-news/10007664/Theatre-director-Patrick-Garland-dies.html \"Theatre director Patrick Garland dies\"], telegraph.co.uk, 19 April 2013</ref>\n\n===Animal welfare===\nBastedo was a vegetarian and is the founder of Alexandra Bastedo Champions (ABC) Animal Sanctuary.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alexandra Bastedo|url=http://www.dancingledge.com/words/interviews/alexandra-bastedo.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alexandra Bastedo Biography|url=http://alexandrabastedo.com/biography.html}}</ref> In an interview for the [[BBC]] television series ''Where Are They Now?'' Bastedo provided a glimpse into her private life. She used to be the president of her local [[Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals|RSPCA]] branch but gave up her position in 2008, to dedicate more time to her fast-growing animal sanctuary at her home in [[West Chiltington]], West Sussex.<ref>[http://www.abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/ Alexandra Bastedo Champions Animal Sanctuary]</ref><ref>[http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/8442149.Brighton_screen_star_s_goats_eat_magic_mushrooms/ Brighton screen star's goats eat magic mushrooms]</ref> A journalist who interviewed her husband in 2010 described their domestic surroundings:\n\n{{quote|[W]e sit in his Sussex garden looking towards a small lake with a jetty and a battered rowing boat&nbsp;\u2013 a perfect pastoral scene which could be a stage set. He lives with his wife, the actress Alexandra Bastedo, who remains startlingly beautiful, a couple of Dobermans, some territorial cats, and a menagerie of horses, donkeys, pigs and goats&nbsp;\u2013 Bastedo runs an animal sanctuary. Garland's domain is largely inside the house where he closes doors to keep animals out of rooms lined with 12,000 books.<ref>Penny Wark, ''The Oldie'', November 2010</ref>}}\n\nShe was also a patron to a number of animal welfare organisations including [[Compassion in World Farming]], [[Wildlife Aid Foundation]], [[National Animal Welfare Trust]], Greyhounds in Need and Naturewatch.<ref>{{cite web|title=ABC Animal Sanctuary |url=http://www.abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723021240/http://abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |archivedate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nBastado died from cancer on 12 January 2014, aged 67, in hospital in Worthing, England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25708277|title=Alexandra Bastedo dies aged 67|publisher=[[BBC NEWS]]|date=13 January 2014}}</ref> She was buried next to her husband Patrick Garland at St. Mary's Church, [[Sullington]], West Sussex. The service was conducted by her local vicar and friend, Revd Derek Spencer who had overseen the funeral of her husband Patrick less than one year earlier.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Alexandra Bastedo, ''Beware Dobermanns, Donkeys and Ducks'' (Parkwest: Robson Books, 1998) {{ISBN|9780860519737}}.\n* Alexandra Bastedo and Jeannie Kemnitzer, ''Canine Care and Cuisine: The Healthy Dog Book'' (Parkwest: Robson Books, 2000) {{ISBN|9781861051189}}.\n* Alexandra Bastedo and Jeannie Kemnitzer, ''The Healthy Cat Book: Feline Care and Cuisine'' (Parkwest: Robson Books, 2000) {{ISBN|9781861051783}}.\n* Alexandra Bastedo and Jeannie Kemnitzer, ''Canine care & cuisine: The Healthy Dog Book'' (Parkwest: Robson, 2000) {{ISBN|9781861051189}}.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[13 Frightened Girls]]'' (aka ''The Candy Web'') (1963) \u2013 Alex \u2013 England\n* ''[[The Liquidator (1965 film)|The Liquidator]]'' (1965) \u2013 Radio Operator (uncredited)\n* ''[[Doctor in Clover]]'' (1966) \u2013 Nurse at Party (uncredited)\n* ''[[That Riviera Touch]]'' (1966) \u2013 Girl at Roulette Table\n* ''[[Casino Royale (1967 film)|Casino Royale]]'' (1967) \u2013 Meg\n* ''[[I Can't... I Can't|Wedding Night]]'' (1970) \u2013 Gloria \u2013 Girl Friend\n* ''[[My Lover, My Son]]'' (1970) \u2013 Cicely Clarkson\n* ''[[A Promise of Bed|This, That and the Other]]'' (1970) \u2013 Angie\n* ''The Kashmiri Run'' (1970)\n* ''[[The Blood Spattered Bride]]'' (1972) \u2013 Mircalla Karstein\n* ''I Hate My Body'' (1974) \u2013 Leda Schmidt\n* ''[[The Ghoul (1975 film)|The Ghoul]]'' (1975) \u2013 Angela\n* ''El Clan de los Nazarenos'' (1975) \u2013 Arima\n* ''Tu dios y mi infierno'' (1976) \u2013 Liselotte\n* ''[[Find the Lady (1976 film)|Find the Lady]]'' (1976) \u2013 Victoria\n* ''The Man Inside'' (1976, TV movie) \u2013 Joan Lytton\n* ''La Gioconda est\u00e1 triste'' (1977)\n* ''El Mir\u00f3n'' (1977) \u2013 Elena \u2013 wife\n* ''Cabo de vara'' (1978)\n* ''Stigma'' (1980) \u2013 Anna\n* ''[[A Choice of Two]]'' (1981) \n* ''[[Draw!]]'' (1984, TV movie) \u2013 Bess, Harry's Girlfriend in Bell City / member of acting troupe\n* ''La veritat oculta'' (1987) \u2013 Agnes / Chiromancer\n* ''[[Batman Begins]]'' (2005) \u2013 Gotham Society Dame\n\n==Television==\n* ''The Count of Monte Cristo'' (TV series, 1964) \u2013 Ren\u00e9e de Saint-M\u00e9ran\n* ''[[The Scales of Justice]]'' (episode ''The Haunted Man'' 1966) \u2013 Laura\n* ''The Wednesday Play'' (1966) (TV) \u2013 The Girl\n* ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'' (episode \"[[List of The Saint episodes|The Counterfeit Countess]]\", 1967) \u2013 Mireille / Joan Vendel\n* ''[[The Champions]]'' (TV series, 1968\u201369) \u2013 Sharron Macready\n* ''[[Randall and Hopkirk (Deceased)]]'' (episode \"[[Whoever Heard of a Ghost Dying?]]\", 1969) \u2013 Carol Latimer\n* ''Codename'' (1970) (TV series) \u2013 Diana Dalzell\n* ''[[From a Bird's Eye View]]'' (episode \"Sicillian Affair\", 1970) \u2013 Lisa Vespucci\n* ''[[The Aphrodite Inheritance]]'' (miniseries, 1979) \u2013 Helene\n* ''Legend of the Champions'' (TV, 1983) \u2013 Sharron Macready\n* ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'' (episode \"Fat\", 1992) \u2013 Penny Caspar-Moorse\n* ''[[EastEnders]]'' (2008\u20132009) \u2013 Cynthia (final television appearance)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk Official Alexandra Bastedo Champions Animal Sanctuary site]\n*[http://www.alexandra-bastedo.com/index.html Official website]\n*[http://www.tv.com/people/alexandra-bastedo/ Alexandra Bastedo] at [[TV.com]]\n*{{IMDb name|0060406}}\n*[http://www.bristol.ac.uk/theatrecollection/search/people_sub_plays?forename=Alexandra&surname=BASTEDO&job=Actor&pid=5849&image_view=Yes&x=19&y=17 Selected performances in Bristol University Theatre Archive]\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/alexandra-bastedo-costar-of-the-late1960s-science-fiction-espionage-series-the-champions-who-went-on-to-run-an-animal-sanctuary-9057110.html Obituary] in The Independent by [[Marcus Williamson]]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bastedo, Alexandra}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:21st-century English actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Sussex]]\n[[Category:Keepers of animal sanctuaries]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:English film actresses]]\n[[Category:English people of Canadian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:English people of French descent]]\n[[Category:English people of German descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Scottish descent]]\n[[Category:English people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:English soap opera actresses]]\n[[Category:English television actresses]]\n[[Category:People educated at Brighton and Hove High School]]\n[[Category:People from Hove]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Actresses of German descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British actress}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Alexandra Bastedo\n| image       = File:Alexandra Bastedo The Champions 1968.jpg\n| caption     = Bastedo in 1968\n| birthname   = Alexandra Lendon Bastedo\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date |df=yes|1946|03|09}}\n| birth_place = [[Hove]], Sussex, England\n| death_date  = {{death date and age |df=yes|2014|01|12|1946|03|09}}\n| death_place = Worthing, England\n| occupation  = Actress and writer\n| yearsactive = 1962\u20132014\n| spouse      = {{marriage|[[Patrick Garland]]|1980|2013|end=died}}\n}}\n\n'''Alexandra Lendon Bastedo''' (9 March 1946 \u2013 12 January 2014) was a British actress, best known for her role as secret agent Sharron Macready in the 1968 British espionage/science fiction adventure series ''[[The Champions]]''. She has been cited as a [[sex symbol]] of the 1960s and 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.express.co.uk/expressyourself/195819/What-happened-to-the-70s-sexpots |title=WHAT HAPPENED TO THE 70S SEXPOTS? |work=[[Daily Express]] |date=27 August 2010 |accessdate=3 November 2010}}</ref> Bastedo was a [[vegetarian]] and [[animal welfare]] advocate, and wrote a number of books on both subjects.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alexandra Bastedo |url=http://www.abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723021240/http://abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |archivedate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBastedo was born in [[Hove]], England. Her mother was of French, German and Italian descent while her Canadian-born father was of Spanish, Dutch, Scottish and native American extraction.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/obituary-alexandra-bastedo-actress-1-3266841|title=Obituary: Alexandra Bastedo, actress|last=Steven|first=Alasdair|date=14 January 2014|website=The Scotsman|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-10-11}}</ref> She attended [[Brighton and Hove High School]] and Brighton School of Drama.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:The Champions.JPG|right|thumb|250px|Alexandra Bastedo with her co-stars [[William Gaunt]] and [[Stuart Damon]] in ''[[The Champions]]''.]]\nShe made her film debut as one of the title characters in [[William Castle]]'s poorly received ''[[13 Frightened Girls]]'' (1963). Bastedo received notice on the European continent, earning her the nickname, \"La Bastedo\". Although most familiar to viewers of 1960s TV, she was also known for her multilingual skills, speaking Italian, Spanish, French and German. This skill brought her to the attention of [[10 Downing Street]] to assist with translations and landed her the role of co-presenter of [[Miss World]] competitions with [[Peter Marshall (UK broadcaster)|Peter Marshall]] in the 1980s.\n\nIn 1979, she played in the series ''[[The Aphrodite Inheritance]]''. In 1988, Bastedo was the cover star for '[[Rank (album)|Rank]]', a live album by British band [[The Smiths]] that charted at number 2 on the British Album charts. In 1991, she appeared in a notable production of the psychological thriller ''[[Dangerous Obsession]]'' by [[N.J. Crisp]], opposite [[Marc Sinden]] and [[John Challis]], at the [[Mill at Sonning]]. In 1992, she appeared in \"Fat\" \u2013 the second broadcast episode of ''[[Absolutely Fabulous]]'', playing a 1960s model associate of Edina and Patsy. She was seen in two episodes of ''[[The Saint (TV series)|The Saint]]'' series, alongside [[Roger Moore]].\n\nIn 2006, Bastedo was reunited for the first time with her co-stars from ''[[The Champions]]'' to provide commentaries and an interview for a DVD release of the show. Still working as an actress, she appeared in ''[[Batman Begins]]'', and touring theatres in 2006 with a production of ''Beyond Reasonable Doubt'' alongside [[Leslie Grantham]] and [[Simon Ward]]. In 2008, she joined the cast of ''[[EastEnders]]'', playing Cynthia.<ref>[http://www.people.co.uk/news/tm_headline=60s-sexbomb-in-square%26method=full%26objectid=20607232%26siteid=93463-name_page News report on Bastedo]</ref><ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/latest/2008/08/28/exclusive-60s-star-alexandra-bastedo-is-new-eastender-115875-20714748/ Article in ''The Mirror Online'' about Bastedo]</ref> In January 2008, she appeared as co-presenter (with [[Ed Stewart]]) of \"The Magic of Mantovani\" at Lighthouse, Poole. The success of this concert led, the following year, to a second concert at the same venue, with the [[Mantovani|Mantovani Orchestra]], which she again co-presented.\n\n==Personal life==\nShe dated [[David Frost]] and [[Omar Sharif]] but turned down the advances of [[Steve McQueen]] who, she recalled, propositioned her with the line \"My wife doesn\u2019t understand me\". In the case of Sharif, the liaison lasted only a few weeks because of the actor's bridge-playing habit, his odd hours and that he took telephone numbers from other women.<ref>{{cite news|title=Alexandra Bastedo \u2013 obituary|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/10569081/Alexandra-Bastedo-obituary.html|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=3 Jan 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Mike Tomkies]], the Fleet Street journalist who abandoned the life of a celebrity reporter to live alone in the wilderness, lived with her for a while in Canada, and they talked of marriage, but she was prohibited from marrying by a contract for ''The Champions'' (1968 to 69). He said that she was the most stunningly beautiful creature he had ever seen.<ref>Telegraph obituary 15.11.16</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Alexandra married [[Patrick Garland]],<ref name=\"BBC13\">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-22232389 \"Patrick Garland, theatre producer and director, dies aged 78\"], BBC News, 20 April 2013</ref> a director, writer and actor, at [[Chichester Cathedral]]; he became a long-serving director of the [[Chichester Festival Theatre]].<ref>''Who's Who'' (annually), entry for Patrick Garland</ref> Bastedo wrote a memoir, ''Beware Dobermanns, Donkeys and Ducks'', as well as several books on caring for cats and dogs. Her husband died on 19 April 2013.<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/theatre/theatre-news/10007664/Theatre-director-Patrick-Garland-dies.html \"Theatre director Patrick Garland dies\"], telegraph.co.uk, 19 April 2013</ref>\n\n===Animal welfare===\nBastedo was a vegetarian and is the founder of Alexandra Bastedo Champions (ABC) Animal Sanctuary.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alexandra Bastedo|url=http://www.dancingledge.com/words/interviews/alexandra-bastedo.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alexandra Bastedo Biography|url=http://alexandrabastedo.com/biography.html}}</ref> In an interview for the [[BBC]] television series ''Where Are They Now?'' Bastedo provided a glimpse into her private life. She used to be the president of her local [[Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals|RSPCA]] branch but gave up her position in 2008, to dedicate more time to her fast-growing animal sanctuary at her home in [[West Chiltington]], West Sussex.<ref>[http://www.abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/ Alexandra Bastedo Champions Animal Sanctuary]</ref><ref>[http://www.theargus.co.uk/news/8442149.Brighton_screen_star_s_goats_eat_magic_mushrooms/ Brighton screen star's goats eat magic mushrooms]</ref> A journalist who interviewed her husband in 2010 described their domestic surroundings:\n\n{{quote|[W]e sit in his Sussex garden looking towards a small lake with a jetty and a battered rowing boat&nbsp;\u2013 a perfect pastoral scene which could be a stage set. He lives with his wife, the actress Alexandra Bastedo, who remains startlingly beautiful, a couple of Dobermans, some territorial cats, and a menagerie of horses, donkeys, pigs and goats&nbsp;\u2013 Bastedo runs an animal sanctuary. Garland's domain is largely inside the house where he closes doors to keep animals out of rooms lined with 12,000 books.<ref>Penny Wark, ''The Oldie'', November 2010</ref>}}\n\nShe was also a patron to a number of animal welfare organisations including [[Compassion in World Farming]], [[Wildlife Aid Foundation]], [[National Animal Welfare Trust]], Greyhounds in Need and Naturewatch.<ref>{{cite web|title=ABC Animal Sanctuary |url=http://www.abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130723021240/http://abcanimalsanctuary.co.uk/page_2333988.html |archivedate=23 July 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nBastado died from cancer on 12 January 2014, aged 67, in hospital in Worthing, England.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-25708277|title=Alexandra Bastedo dies aged 67|publisher=[[BBC NEWS]]|date=13 January 2014}}</ref> She was buried next to her husband Patrick Garland at St. Mary's Church, [[Sullington]], West Sussex. The service was conducted by her local vicar and friend, Revd Derek Spencer who had overseen the funeral of her husband Patrick less than one year earlier.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Alexandra Bastedo, ''Beware Dobermanns, Donkeys and Ducks'' (Parkwest: Robson Books, 1998) {{ISBN|9780860519737}}.\n* Alexandra Bastedo and Jeannie Kemnitzer, ''Canine Care and Cuisine: The Healthy Dog Book'' (Parkwest: Robson Books, 2000) {{ISBN|9781861051189}}.\n* Alexandra Bastedo and Jeannie Kemnitzer, ''The Healthy Cat Book: Feline Care and Cuisine'' (Parkwest: Robson Books, 2000) {{ISBN|9781861051783}}.\n* Alexandra Bastedo and Jeannie Kemnitzer, ''Canine care & cuisine: The Healthy Dog Book'' (Parkwest: Robson, 2000) {{ISBN|9781861051189}}.\n\n==Filmography==\n* ''[[13 Frightened Girls]]'' (aka ''The Candy Web'') (1963) \u2013 Alex \u2013 England\n* ''[[The Liquidator (1965 film)|The Liquidator]]'' (1965) \u2013 Radio Operator (uncredited)\n* ''[[Doctor in Clover]]'' (1966) \u2013 Nurse at Party (uncredited)\n* ''[[That Riviera Touch]]'' (1966) \u2013 Girl at Roulette Table\n* ''[[Casino Royale (1967 film)|Casino Royale]]'' (1967) \u2013 Meg\n* ''[[