{"title_page": "Lakshman Kiriella", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable|Hon.]]\n| name = Lakshman Kiriella\n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0dbd\u0d9a\u0dca\u0dc2\u0dca\u0db8\u0db1\u0dca \u0d9a\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dd2\u0d87\u0dbd\u0dca\u0dbd}} <br /> {{lang|ta|\u0bb2\u0b95\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b8e\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2}}\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| image = \n| imagesize = 250px\n| office1 = [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House of Sri Lanka]]\n| president1 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Nimal Siripala De Silva]]\n| successor1 = [[Dinesh Gunawardena]]\n| term_start1 = 20 January 2015\n| term_end1 = December 2019\n| office2 = [[Minister of Public Enterprise, Kandyan Heritage & Kandy Development]]\n| president2 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start2 = 25 February 2018\n| term_end2 = 22 November 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Kabir Hashim]]\n| successor2 = \n| office3 = [[Ministry of Higher Education (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Higher Education and Highways]]\n| president3 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start3 = 14 October 2015\n| term_end3 = 25 February 2018\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 = [[Kabir Hashim]]\n| office4 = [[Ministry of Plantation Industries|Minister of Plantation Industries]]\n| president4 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start4 = 12 January 2015\n| term_end4 = 17 August 2015\n| predecessor4 = [[Mahinda Samarasinghe]]\n| successor4 = \n| president5 = [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start5 = 12 December 2001\n| term_end5 = 2 April 2004\n| predecessor5 = \n| successor5 = \n| constituency_MP6 = [[Kandy Electoral District|Kandy District]]\n| parliament6 = Sri Lankan\n| majority6 = \n| term_start6 = 1989\n| term_end6 = \n| predecessor6 = \n| successor6 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1948|02|02|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Sri Lanka]]n\n| party = [[United National Party]]<small> (2001&ndash;present) </small> <br /> [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] <small> (1989&ndash;2001) </small>\n| otherparty = \n| occupation = \n| spouse = Charmaine n\u00e9e Jayawardena\n| partner = \n| relations = \n| children = Kishanee, Chami, Dinuk L. B.\n| residence = Pelawatta\n| alma_mater = [[Royal College, Colombo]]\n| profession = [[Lawyer]]\n| rank = \n| branch = \n| unit = \n| allegiance = \n| serviceyears = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Lakshman Bandara Kiriella''', [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|MP]] (born 2 February 1948) is a [[Sri Lanka]]n politician and [[lawyer]]. He is a [[Member of Parliament]] from the [[Kandy Electoral District|Kandy District]], former [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House]] of the parliament. Also he held office as Minister of Public Enterprises and Kandy Development and as [[Ministry of Higher Education and Highways|Minister of Higher Education and Highways]] from 2015\u20132019. \n\nEducated at [[Royal College, Colombo]] and [[Sri Lanka Law College]], he became a practicing lawyer before entering politics.  He has elected to Parliament in 1989, he has been a Member ever since. He has served as the Minister of Tourism and Sports and the Deputy minister of Foreign Affairs. In 2015 he was appointed as the Leader of the House of the United National Party Government under Prime Minister [[Ranil Wickremesinghe|Ranil Wickramasinghe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2010/07/18/kiriella-speaks/|title=Kiriella Speaks {{!}} The Sunday Leader|last=Wickrematunge|first=Raisa|date=|website=The Sunday Leader|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref>\n\nHe is married to Charmaine Jayawardena and they have two daughters, Kishanee and Chami, and one son, Dinuk L. B.\n\nIn October 2018 the [[Asgiri Maha Viharaya|Asgiriya Chapter]] of [[Siam Nikaya]] conferred the title of [[Shasanamamaka Jana Prasadini]] on Kiriella, in recognition of his service to Buddhism and society.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2018/10/22/local/166199/shasanamamaka-jana-prasadini-title-minister-kiriella|title=Shasanamamaka Jana Prasadini title for Minister Kiriella|newspaper=[[The Daily News (Sri Lanka)|The Daily News]]|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n===[[E04 expressway (Sri Lanka)|Central Expressway]] Construction ===\n[[E04 expressway (Sri Lanka)|Central expressway of Sri Lanka]] (E04 expressway) planned to construct in four phases to link [[Kadawatha]] to [[Kandy]]. However, the construction of phase one and phase three were delayed as Chinese and Japanese loans weren't receiving on time. Phase two of the project ([[Mirigama]] to [[Katugastota]]) funded by the Sri Lankan government and construction carrying out by local constructors. There are some allegations that phase two construction carrying out by companies attached to Kiriella<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visitsrilanka.com/news/the-tale-of-lakshman-kiriella-the-sinners-trying-to-destroy-the-expressway-project/|title=The tale of Lakshman Kiriella the sinners trying to destroy the expressway project - VisitSriLanka.com|last=Lanka|first=Visit Sri|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dbsjeyaraj.com/dbsj/archives/55917|title=Cabinet Colleagues In Heated Argument With Highways Minister Lakshman Kiriella Over Potuhera to Galagedara Construction in Central Expressway Project|last=Administrator|date=2017-10-16|website=dbsjeyaraj.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>. [[Committee On Public Enterprises (Sri Lanka)|COPE]] decided to investigate tender procedure of central expressway project due to allegations of misappropriation of public funds<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/171791/cope-investigates-central-expressway-tender|title=COPE investigates Central Expressway tender|website=Hiru News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2017/09/20/ags-department-investigate-central-expressway-tender-process/173061/|title=AG's Dept to investigate central expressway tender process - Sri Lanka Latest News|date=2017-09-20|website=Sri Lanka News - Newsfirst|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>. And MP. [[Anura Kumara Dissanayaka|Anura Kumara Dissanayake]] mentioned in parliament recalling a statement by former president [[Maithripala Sirisena]] that tender procedures has been violated while offering contracts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Central-Expressway-s-construction-work-will-go-ahead-PM/108-136267|title=Central Expressway's construction work will go ahead: PM|website=www.dailymirror.lk|language=English|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Responding to media, minister of parliament [[Wimal Weerawansa]] blamed that former minister Kiriella and his daughter converted central expressway project into their money making venture<ref>{{Citation|title=Central Expressway Project : The new money-maker for MPs and Ministers?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=84i2cyPOcOU|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/09/04/central-expressway-project-the-new-money-maker-for-mps-and-ministers/|title=Central Expressway Project : The new money-maker for MPs and Ministers? - Sri Lanka Latest News|date=2019-09-04|website=Sri Lanka News - Newsfirst|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>. \n\n=== Recruiting Political Supporters to RDA ===\n[[Presidential Commission of Inquiry]] (PCoI) probing corruption in good governance (Yahapalana ) government conducted inquiry on backdoor appointments given by former minister to UNP supporters.He was accused for recruiting UMP members as public liaison officers and consultants to the [[Road Development Authority]] (RDA) without conducting interviews, checking qualifications and assigning duties <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=211127|title=Minister Kiriella justifies backdoor appointments for party supporters|last=Kuruwita|first=Rathindra|date=24 September 2019|website=www.island.lk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://srilankabrief.org/2016/07/minister-kiriellas-deception-exposed/|title=Minister Kiriella\u2019s Deception Exposed {{!}} Sri Lanka Brief|last=|first=|date=23 July 2016|website=Sri Lanka Brief|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref>. Former minister denied allegations that those recruitments cost Rs. 62.87 million to government<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100324200248/http://www.parliament.lk/directory_of_members/ViewMember.do?memID=75 Biographies of Member of Parliament]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/rcob.html Right Royal rally of old Royalists in     the Sri Lanka Parliament]\n\n{{Sri Lankan Sports ministers}}\n{{Members of 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Kandy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiriella, Lakshman}}\n[[Category:Sports ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:United National Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sri Lanka Law College]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Higher education ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox MP\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Honourable|Hon.]]\n| name = Lakshman Kiriella\n| native_name = {{lang|si|\u0dbd\u0d9a\u0dca\u0dc2\u0dca\u0db8\u0db1\u0dca \u0d9a\u0dd2\u0dbb\u0dd2\u0d87\u0dbd\u0dca\u0dbd}} <br /> {{lang|ta|\u0bb2\u0b95\u0bcd\u0bb8\u0bcd\u0bae\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bbf\u0bb0\u0bbf\u0b8e\u0bb2\u0bcd\u0bb2}}\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n| image = \n| imagesize = 250px\n| office1 = [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House of Sri Lanka]]\n| president1 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Nimal Siripala De Silva]]\n| successor1 = [[Dinesh Gunawardena]]\n| term_start1 = 20 January 2015\n| term_end1 = December 2019\n| office2 = [[Minister of Public Enterprise, Kandyan Heritage & Kandy Development]]\n| president2 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start2 = 25 February 2018\n| term_end2 = 22 November 2019\n| predecessor2 = [[Kabir Hashim]]\n| successor2 = \n| office3 = [[Ministry of Higher Education (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Higher Education and Highways]]\n| president3 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister3 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start3 = 14 October 2015\n| term_end3 = 25 February 2018\n| predecessor3 = \n| successor3 = [[Kabir Hashim]]\n| office4 = [[Ministry of Plantation Industries|Minister of Plantation Industries]]\n| president4 = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start4 = 12 January 2015\n| term_end4 = 17 August 2015\n| predecessor4 = [[Mahinda Samarasinghe]]\n| successor4 = \n| president5 = [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| term_start5 = 12 December 2001\n| term_end5 = 2 April 2004\n| predecessor5 = \n| successor5 = \n| constituency_MP6 = [[Kandy Electoral District|Kandy District]]\n| parliament6 = Sri Lankan\n| majority6 = \n| term_start6 = 1989\n| term_end6 = \n| predecessor6 = \n| successor6 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1948|02|02|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[Sri Lanka]]n\n| party = [[United National Party]]<small> (2001&ndash;present) </small> <br /> [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] <small> (1989&ndash;2001) </small>\n| otherparty = \n| occupation = \n| spouse = Charmaine n\u00e9e Jayawardena\n| partner = \n| relations = \n| children = Kishanee, Chami, Dinuk L. B.\n| residence = Pelawatta\n| alma_mater = [[Royal College, Colombo]]\n| profession = [[Lawyer]]\n| rank = \n| branch = \n| unit = \n| allegiance = \n| serviceyears = \n| signature = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Lakshman Bandara Kiriella''', [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|MP]] (born 2 February 1948) is a [[Sri Lanka]]n politician and [[lawyer]]. He is a [[Member of Parliament]] from the [[Kandy Electoral District|Kandy District]], former [[Leader of the House (Sri Lanka)|Leader of the House]] of the parliament. Also he held office as Minister of Public Enterprises and Kandy Development and as [[Ministry of Higher Education and Highways|Minister of Higher Education and Highways]] from 2015-2019. \n\nEducated at [[Royal College, Colombo]] and [[Sri Lanka Law College]], he became a practicing lawyer before entering politics.  He has elected to Parliament in 1989, he has been a Member ever since. He has served as the Minister of Tourism and Sports and the Deputy minister of Foreign Affairs. In 2015 he was appointed as the Leader of the House of the United National Party Government under Prime Minister [[Ranil Wickremesinghe|Ranil Wickramasinghe]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thesundayleader.lk/2010/07/18/kiriella-speaks/|title=Kiriella Speaks {{!}} The Sunday Leader|last=Wickrematunge|first=Raisa|date=|website=The Sunday Leader|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref>\n\nHe is married to Charmaine Jayawardena and they have two daughters, Kishanee and Chami, and one son, Dinuk L. B.\n\nIn October 2018 the [[Asgiri Maha Viharaya|Asgiriya Chapter]] of [[Siam Nikaya]] conferred the title of [[Shasanamamaka Jana Prasadini]] on Kiriella, in recognition of his service to Buddhism and society.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailynews.lk/2018/10/22/local/166199/shasanamamaka-jana-prasadini-title-minister-kiriella|title=Shasanamamaka Jana Prasadini title for Minister Kiriella|newspaper=[[The Daily News (Sri Lanka)|The Daily News]]|date=22 October 2018|accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n===[[E04 expressway (Sri Lanka)|Central Expressway]] Construction ===\n[[E04 expressway (Sri Lanka)|Central expressway of Sri Lanka]] (E04 expressway) planned to construct in four phases to link [[Kadawatha]] to [[Kandy]]. However, the construction of phase one and phase three were delayed as Chinese and Japanese loans weren't receiving on time. Phase two of the project ([[Mirigama]] to [[Katugastota]]) funded by the Sri Lankan government and construction carrying out by local constructors. There are some allegations that phase two construction carrying out by companies attached to Kiriella<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://visitsrilanka.com/news/the-tale-of-lakshman-kiriella-the-sinners-trying-to-destroy-the-expressway-project/|title=The tale of Lakshman Kiriella the sinners trying to destroy the expressway project - VisitSriLanka.com|last=Lanka|first=Visit Sri|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dbsjeyaraj.com/dbsj/archives/55917|title=Cabinet Colleagues In Heated Argument With Highways Minister Lakshman Kiriella Over Potuhera to Galagedara Construction in Central Expressway Project|last=Administrator|date=2017-10-16|website=dbsjeyaraj.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>. [[Committee On Public Enterprises (Sri Lanka)|COPE]] decided to investigate tender procedure of central expressway project due to allegations of misappropriation of public funds<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/171791/cope-investigates-central-expressway-tender|title=COPE investigates Central Expressway tender|website=Hiru News|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2017/09/20/ags-department-investigate-central-expressway-tender-process/173061/|title=AG's Dept to investigate central expressway tender process - Sri Lanka Latest News|date=2017-09-20|website=Sri Lanka News - Newsfirst|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>. And MP. [[Anura Kumara Dissanayaka|Anura Kumara Dissanayake]] mentioned in parliament recalling a statement by former president [[Maithripala Sirisena]] that tender procedures has been violated while offering contracts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/breaking_news/Central-Expressway-s-construction-work-will-go-ahead-PM/108-136267|title=Central Expressway's construction work will go ahead: PM|website=www.dailymirror.lk|language=English|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Responding to media, minister of parliament [[Wimal Weerawansa]] blamed that former minister Kiriella and his daughter converted central expressway project into their money making venture<ref>{{Citation|title=Central Expressway Project : The new money-maker for MPs and Ministers?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=84i2cyPOcOU|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsfirst.lk/2019/09/04/central-expressway-project-the-new-money-maker-for-mps-and-ministers/|title=Central Expressway Project : The new money-maker for MPs and Ministers? - Sri Lanka Latest News|date=2019-09-04|website=Sri Lanka News - Newsfirst|language=en|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref>. \n\n=== Recruiting Political Supporters to RDA ===\n[[Presidential Commission of Inquiry]] (PCoI) probing corruption in good governance (Yahapalana ) government conducted inquiry on backdoor appointments given by former minister to UNP supporters.He was accused for recruiting UMP members as public liaison officers and consultants to the [[Road Development Authority]] (RDA) without conducting interviews, checking qualifications and assigning duties <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=211127|title=Minister Kiriella justifies backdoor appointments for party supporters|last=Kuruwita|first=Rathindra|date=24 September 2019|website=www.island.lk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://srilankabrief.org/2016/07/minister-kiriellas-deception-exposed/|title=Minister Kiriella\u2019s Deception Exposed {{!}} Sri Lanka Brief|last=|first=|date=23 July 2016|website=Sri Lanka Brief|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-07}}</ref>. Former minister denied allegations that those recruitments cost Rs. 62.87 million to government<ref name=\":0\" />.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20100324200248/http://www.parliament.lk/directory_of_members/ViewMember.do?memID=75 Biographies of Member of Parliament]\n*[http://www.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~lkawgw/rcob.html Right Royal rally of old Royalists in     the Sri Lanka Parliament]\n\n{{Sri Lankan Sports ministers}}\n{{Members of 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the Sri Lankan Parliament from Kandy}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiriella, Lakshman}}\n[[Category:Sports ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:United National Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal College, Colombo]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Sri Lanka Law College]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 10th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 13th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Higher education ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n\n\n{{SriLanka-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2015-2019 \u2192 2015\u20132019", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lakshman_Kiriella"}
{"title_page": "FIBA Oceania Women's Championship", "text_new": "{{For|the men's tournament|FIBA Oceania Championship}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox sports league\n| Formerly       = \n| logo           = \n| pixels         = \n| caption        = \n| sport          = Basketball\n| fame           = \n| motto          = \n| founded        = 1974\n| folded         = 2015\n| replaced       = [[FIBA Women's Asia Cup]]\n| inaugural      = [[FIBA Oceania Championship for Women 1974|1974]]\n| teams          = 2\n| country        = [[FIBA Oceania]] member nations\n| continent      = [[FIBA Oceania]] ([[Oceania]])\n| champion       = {{bkw|AUS}} (15th title)\n| most_champs    = {{bkw|AUS}} (15 titles)\n| qualification  = \n| website        = [http://www.fibaoceania.com/ www.FIBAOceania.com]\n| singles        = \n| ceo            = \n| Director       = \n| TV             = \n| related_comps  = \n| Founder        = \n}}\n\nThe '''FIBA Oceania Women's Championship''' was the women's [[basketball]] continental championship of [[Oceania]], played biennially under the auspices of the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Basketball]], the basketball [[sport governing body]], and the [[FIBA Oceania|Oceanian zone]] thereof.  The tournament also serves to [[multi-stage tournament|qualify]] teams for participation in the quadrennial [[FIBA World Championship for Women]] and the [[Basketball at the Summer Olympics|Olympic basketball tournament]].\n\nBeginning in 2017, all FIBA continental championships for women will be held on a two-year cycle, and the continental championships will be part of the qualifying process for either the World Cup or Olympics. The 2015 Oceanian Championships were the last Oceanian Championships to ever be held as starting 2017, the tournament will merge with the [[FIBA Asia Championship]] to give way for the '''FIBA Asia-Pacific Championship'''<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.fiba.com/pages/eng/fc/news/presRele/p/newsid/54422/presReleArti.html |title=Central Board gives green light to new format and calendar of competition |publisher=FIBA |date=11 November 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Summaries==\nResults highlighted in blue are Olympic qualifiers, those which aren't are World Championship qualifiers.\n\nAs host nation for the 2000 Olympic Games in [[Sydney]], [[Australia women's national basketball team|Australia]] gained automatic qualification to the Olympics. The withdrawal of American Samoa meant that [[New Zealand women's national basketball team|New Zealand]] won the 1999 tournament through default. Consequently, the FIBA Oceania qualifier into the 2000 Sydney Olympics was [[New Zealand women's national basketball team|New Zealand]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fibaoceania.com/fileadmin/user_upload/_temp_/The_Landon_Trophy_-Bckgrnd_Article.pdf |title=The Landon Trophy for competition between Australian and New Zealand |publisher=FIBA |accessdate=7 September 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130520224106/http://www.fibaoceania.com/fileadmin/user_upload/_temp_/The_Landon_Trophy_-Bckgrnd_Article.pdf |archivedate=20 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%; width:100%\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2 width=5%|Year\n!rowspan=2 width=4%|Host\n!colspan=5|Qualification series\n!rowspan=2 width=6%|Bronze medallists\n|-\n!width=6%|Gold\n!width=6%|Game 1\n!width=6%|Game 2\n!width=6%|Game 3\n!width=6%|Silver\n|-\n|1974<br />''[[FIBA Oceania Championship for Women 1974|Details]]''\n|align=left|{{flagcountry|Australia}}\n|'''{{Bkw-big|AUS}}'''\n|'''69\u201342'''\n|'''72\u201344'''\n|'''75\u201355'''\n|{{Bkw-big|NZL}}\n|bgcolor=#efefef rowspan=7|No third team competed\n|-\n|1978<br />''[[FIBA Oceania Championship for Women 1978|Details]]''\n|align=left|{{flagcountry|NZL}}\n|'''{{Bkw-big|AUS}}'''\n|'''68\u201337'''\n|'''63\u201333'''\n|'''89\u201332'''\n|{{Bkw-big|NZL}}\n|-\n|1982<br />''[[1982 FIBA Oceania Championship for Women|Details]]''\